{"/service/ndnp/tu/batch_tu_anita_ver01/data/sn85038531/00415621255/1920073001/1059.xml":{"full_text":"I:\nj I\nflim.nnKVF.Rv\nINTERESTING\nTHE CHATTANOOGA NEWS, CHATTANOOGA. TENN., FRIDAY, JULY 30, 1920.\nNational City Bank of New\nYork Comments on Busi-\nness Conditions.\nCROP OUTLOOK IS FINE\nThe general business outlook is ex\ntremely Interesting acoordlns; to the\nmonthly report of tha National Cltx\nBank of Chicago. According to tha\nstatement, \"there ara many uncertain\nIlea to reckon with, which In a nn.l\ndential year are capable of developing\niiiipunani compucaiiona.\n\"There la nothing In tha caninnto-n\no far to Indicate that, the presidential\n,umei win nave an adverse innuenca\nupon general business.- Credit atraln\nl the world over la a aerloua factor In\nmmmm\nreitrlotlnf operation aril forcing len\nders to reiuaa accommodation to none\nessential enterprises. There, la no\ndoubt, however, but that the country\nwill marga from tola experience all\nright and that there la abundant pros\nperity ahead. .But we are In the midst\nof a world-wide readjustment which\nmay be expected to continue until the\nabnormal oommodlty prlcea of the war\nperioa nave given way to the more\nreasonable quotations of peace tlmea.\nThe situation calls for clear-headed\nmanagement on all sldas.\n\"The country la still heavily short of\nbusiness and housing struoturea, but It\nnaa Dean aimcuit to ousn new im\nprovement work during the period when\nthe diversion of open cars to fuel ship\nments exclusively has made It Impos\nsible for builders and contractors to\nobtain necessary supplies. Prices are\nsteadily advancing and In various lo\ncalitles large project enterprises bav\nbeen postponed until more normal con\nditions prevail. There are many thou\nsand people In this country without a\npermanent.: bode and because of exces\nsive .bulliWg costs, owners of old\nhouse! and business structures are ob\ntaining unheard or prices for their\nfoldings. It has been charged In some\ncases that contracts guaranteeing the\ndelivery. of needed material ara being\navoided, so as to secure nigner prices,\ntne supply Deing extremely limited\nNew building projects. In New York\nCity alone are aald to be sufficient to\nconsume all the material that can be\ndelivered wunin tne next eighteen\nmontha. The outlook Is very interest\ning, but sinco conditions are wholly\nnt normal, It is Impossible to 'ell what\nproportion of the presont demand for\nhousing accommodations In the large\ncities can be supplied by the close of\nthis year. A orlsis is likely to develop\nin the fall renting season, when the\ntotal demand for available space will\nprobably reach record-breaking propor\ntion!. Good Investment Bought.\n\"The Investment altaution has shown\ndistinct Improvement owing to the de\nvelopment of a broader Inquiry for high:\ngrade investments following the dis\nbursement last month of the Usual\nsemi-annual dividend and Interest pay\nments. The public response to the\noffering of the Kingdom of Belgium,\n$50,000,000 twenty-five-year 71 per cent\nloan: the government of' Swltserland,\nJ26.uou.ooo twenty-year I per cent loan:\nArmour eV Co., $60,000,000 T per cent\nten-year convertible gold notes, and\nother high-class loans has shown that\na really safe loan Issued at a price to\nyield an Income of from 7H to 8 per\ncent Is finding Increased favor with\nAmerican Investors- This Is a devel\nopment of high Importance, and means\ntliot Investment conlltlcns are Improv\ning and that well selected securities\nDINES PROVIDENT NINE\npresident k. j. Maclellan, of the\nProvident Life and Accident Insurance\ncompany,\" entertained the members of\ntne i-roviueni oamuau team or \"Bit\"\nleague last night at the Oolf and\ncountry ciud. xn, auests were taken\nin macnines irom ine nome onice ol\ntha company at o'clock, and on ar\nrival at tne ciud proceeded to enjoy\nmi wimiimia puui. jiuer a oengnttul\nawlm they proceeded to the dining\nroom, where covera had been laid for\nalxteen. The guests enjoyed a fine\niriea cnicnen dinner.\nAfter th dinner Mr. Maclellan com.\npllmented the members of the team on\ntneir excellent snowing lor the season,\nand commented on the clean sports\nmanship which had been ahown In all\ngames played. Ha pointed out to the\npiayera mat tne Provident was de\nslrous of having its players play to\nwin, but to win the game on Its merits\nonly. Mr. Maclellan then called on\nCnptaln Gilbert, Fitld Manager Davles\nand other members of the. team, .who\nspoke of the ambitions vf the team\nand the Interest they had) taken In tha\ngame.\nJ. J. Kennedy, presdent of the league,\nspoke of the organisation of the \"Bit\"\nleague and Its object, which he aald\nwas to give the boys an opportunity\nof having clean, healthful snort end\nbecoming better acquainted with each\nother. Mr. Kennedy complimented the\nProvident and all teams in the league\nfor the clean manner In which all\ngames had been played, and called ape\ncial attention to the fact that It had\nnot been necessary to call a special\nmeeting of the league to settle any dis\nputes, nor had any disputes of any\nnature been referred to the grievance\ncommittee, which he pleaded as an\nevidence of the quality of the mem\nbers of all teams. Brief talks were also\nmade by Messrs. L. N. Webb. M. E.\nLeSueur and others of the Provident\nhome office staff.\n13\noffered at a price to bring the buyers\nreturn eaual to the prevailing rate\nof the money market will find a rea\nsonably quick sale. This Is not strange\nir. view of the extraordinary low price\nat which tne best securities have been\nselling since the huge reconstruction\ndemands have preased heavily upon the\none market of the world which hns been\nable to make the necessary advances.\nThat the bond market has been free\nfrom inflation is apparent from the\n(act that the average yield on twenty\nhigh-grade railroad bonds at the mid\ndle of July was nearly 6(4 per cent, as\ncompared with 8.48 per cent a year ago\nand 4.66 per cent at that date In 1913.\n\"The crop ouook, considering the\ncondition of all crops, Is excellent and\nlikely to show further Improvement\nduring. this most Important month ot\nthe crop year. Although the govern\nment s July figures for all grains show\n10 per cent less acreage than last year.\ntne promised yield is only 1.1 per ceut\nsmaller and about l per cent below\nthe ten-yeup average. furtliermoi e.\nthe total wheat estimate, while below\nlast year, shews a il.L-llna nf niv i t\nper cent below the rive years prior to\nWIS. The total crop situation Is urcb-\noiy considerably bettor than these\nhgures I ml I oa to, (or weather conditions\nol late have been distinctly favorable\nsmd there is good reaaon to look for\npronounced improvement in the forth\ncoming government report. It la slg\nmilCailt that llOtmtOM lnhM II-\nrice and apples show Improvement as\ncompared with a year ago, with the\n\"untile oi a total food value for all\nv.v,,,. auove tne live-year average.\nThis estimate Is based upon a con\ntinuance or favnraiiu .n,u,iA.\nsuch progressive Improvement as may\nbe reasonably looked for during the\nweens. Tne most trust\nworthy advices provide basis for be\nnevuii, mat tne coming year will wit\nness continued proaperity In the agri\ncultural area, providing the railroads\ngive those communities the shipping\nnn-y require.\nMore .Thrift Kinon\nimTh?. ver\"B\" merchant la finding It\n\".n. t inr upon luuire commit\nments Involving large orders for mer\nchandise at present prices. The clos\ning oi mo mum oi tne American Woolen\nuuiiipnujr Rna tne reduction of worklni\nforces by the Pennsylvania rallroa\nare Indicative of the chanced nnn.ii\ntlons In Industry. Prices of knit goods\nare quotably higher for next spring, as\niiiniiuiaciurers nave peen confronted\nwith increased production costs which\nmake it Impossible for them to (Juote\nlower prices. The demand for non\nessential merchandise, however. Is not\nin it was, aitnougn the work\ning ciassej sre well supplies with\nmoney end are consuming large Quan\ntities or merchandise The purchasing\nuwwrr oi m. country is still very great,\nrut the purchasers are not displaying\nthe happy-go-lucky freedom that they\n\"w momna bro. jn tne con\ntrary, tne average buyer Is seeing to\nIt that his expended dollar Is bringing\nhim a better return thnn It did In the\ndays when the silk mills were doing\nan enormous Dusinesa wnn raw Silk\nquoted In Japan at 115 or 120 a pound.\nLuxury buying Is not the menace that\nIt was,, for the drs'lc reduction in\nmen's clothing and the lower prices\nfor shoes end other apparel has adver\ntised In a remarkable way the new\ntrend In general trade throughout the\nworld.\"\nKnox Safe for\nCol Crabtree\n3h\n904 MARKET ST. THROUGH TO-12 E. NINTH ST.\n-women Hurry! Hurry!\nTake advantage of the extraordinary, values\noffered during our\nJuly Clearance Sale-Now On\nAt this semi-annual event our one aim is to clear out our present stock\nand, make room for Fall and Winter merchandise which is now. on the\nway. Mind you, our stock of 'merchandise is the finest in the city. We\ninvite every thrifty man and woman to come in and see what wonderful\nvalues we are offering.\n20\nIf ever you had a chance to save money, now is your opportunity.\nNo matter what you may purchase, you can rest assured that you are sav\ning many dollars. Don't wait and be sorry after this sale is over. We\ndoubt very much whether an opportunity' of this kind will again present\nitself. Our advice is COME IN AND BE CONVINCED.\nNo Money Down\nWe Are Offering\nthe 'Most Liberal\nCredit Terms\nB\nIS A n o\nWe don't want anyone to stay away from this sale because of not\nhaving the ready cash. Not only are the values offered wonderful, but\nwe offer the most liberal credit terms in the city. On any purchase up\nto $15.00, no down payment is required just take your purchase right\nhome with you and pay to suit your convenience. Should your purchase\namount to $25, $50, $75 or $100, we will cheerfully arrange the terms to\nplease you. Come in don't hesitate no rejl tape or references needed\nto open an account here.\nDon't Miss This Opportunity\nThis is a sale of sales. Come in and convince yourself. The thrifty\nman and woman will need no second invitation. You dont' need the cash\nin order to realize these savings. You can select what you want and have\nit charged.\nTwenty to Fifty Per Cent Off\nON-\nWomen's and Misses' Summer Frocks, Waists, Skirts, Milli\nnery, Silk and Cloth Dresses\nMen's and Young Men's Suits, Boys' Suits, Men's Straw Hats,\nMean's Pants.\ni\nana wdnm\n904 MARKET ST. THROUGH TO 12 E. NINTH ST.\nKnoxvlll. Tenn,, July 10. (Special.)\n\"Knox county is safe for Col. W. R,\nCrabtree In the race for the democratic\ngubernatorial nomination by fully 1,000\nvotes and the majority may reach\n1.600,\" declared former Mayor John E,\nMcMillan, local manager for the Chat\ntanogan, this morning.\n\"Reports rrom every city ward and\nall but one or two rural precincts In\nthe county show that the democrats\nare aroused over the vicious stale tnx\nis.w ana me even more Infamous public\nminim ti ii iii. uooeris minimis\ntratlon, ana that they are preparing to\ni\" innim nvxi i nursiiny ami vote\nior i,oi. jraoiree, giving him an over\nwhelming majority tn this county,'\noontlnued Mr. McMillan.\n\"My estimate of 1.000 malorltv Is\nconservative. We do not wish to claim\nanything that we will not have In the\nprimary, some or tne Koberte ninnn\ngers In this county are making ridic\nulous claims In an effort to keep up\nthe courage of their importers It Is\nlike the colored man whlstllnr fhrmivh\nthe graveyard. No one knows better\nman the local Kolierts manager that\nthe governor cannot possibly receive\nanything like as many votes In Knox\ncounty as they are claim Inn as a ma\nJorlty for him. Col. CraMroe will carry\nme rural precincts nt tne county al\nmost every one of them and the hi\nnemocraiio warns or ureater Knoxvllle\nwill give mm Handsome majorities.\"\nProf. Rupert Reynolds, democrat In\npresidential elector for tha Second con\ngressional district: Judire W. V. Miller.\none of Roberts' campaign manacers In\nthis county two years ago, and Judge\nA. Y. Burrows, well-known member of\nthe Knoxvllle bar, are speaking\nthroughout Knox county this week In\nthe Interest of Col. Crabtree, and they\nreport fine receptions ami overwhelm\ning sentiment among the farmers\nagainst (lov, Koberts.\nFrof. Reynolds savs that ha fella sure\nthat Col. Crabtree will have a ma\njority of 1,000 to 1,800 votes In the\ncounty.\nMURIEL CIGARS\nThere are no suuertor clears made\nthan Muriels. The best of long leaf\ntobacco, properly cured, goes Into the\nmaking of them. A trial will convince\nyou. At all dealers. Chanev-Hnott\nCigar Company, distributors. (Adv.)\nCOULD HARDLY\nGET HIS BREATH\nJohnson's Troubles All Dis\nappear After He Takes\nTanlac.\n\"The way Tanlao built me up proves\nto me that It la a great medicine,\" said\n(lust A. Johnson, of Virginia, Minn, Mr.\nJohnson has been employed by the lu\nluth and Iron Range railroad for thirty\nlive years.\n\"I suffered from stomach trouble In\nits worst stages.\" continued Mr. John\nson.\" \"So much gas formed In my stom\nact after eating 1 could hardly breathe.\nI also had the rheumatism so had In\nmy knees sometimes It was all I could\nC to hobble about and I was so nerv-\ncus that many a night I could not sleep\nat an, ana ny morning I was all tired\nout and weak as If I hadn't been In bed\nat all.\n\"I noticed In the papers about Tan\nlao and gave It a trial, and It's a fact.\nnothing can beat It, for I've taken only\nthree bottles and feel like a new man,\nI eat anything I want now and am never\ntroubled with gas any more; the rheu\nmatism has left me and my nerves are\nsteady as a clock and I get up every\nmorning feel fit and ready for the day's\nwork. Tanlac Is the greatest medicine\nI've seen and I know what I'm talking\nabout, for I have tried nearly every\nthing.\" Tanlac Is sold In Chattanooga by Mor\nrison's three drug stores; Ir. M. O.\nNull, Rldge Junction; Sherman Heights\nriiarmacy. East Chattart oga. (Adv.)\nE5\n3\nif\nIks\n53\nera\nC3\n3\nE3\n3\n3\nIf\nEVERYBODY'S!\nDOING IT NOW! 1\nt' 2\nSales!. Sales and Still More Sales are being held on every hand jj\nso here is our contribution to help you reduce the H. C. L.\nOur original prices do not permit a mark-down of 50 per cent., f j\n33 1-3 per cent, or 20 per cent., but we will go you 50-50 and are if\nreducing every tailored-to-order suit in the house 10 per cent. If\nThis reduction applies to every yard of cloth in our large stock M.\neven serges are not excepted no \"shop-worn\" materials, no l\nout-of-date models, but new Fall Fabrics tailored in the latest jj\nstyles to your individual measures. Fit and workmanship guar- If\nanteed to please you or your money back. l\n$50.00 BAUER SUITS CMK 00 il\nTailored to Order PU.VV j\n$55.00 BAUER SUITS VAQ KA U\nTailored to Order WV.OV\nt V C\"\n$58.50 BAUER SUITS (gKO fiK. 11\nTailored to Order M J\n$60.00 BAUER SUITS- Aft 1\nTailored to Order t,,uu\n$62.50 BAUER SUITS- efcfi OK 1\nTailored to Order wv.&o\n$65.00 BAUER SUITS- $58.50 H\nTailored to Order j\n$70.00 BAUER SUITS $63.00 P\nTailored to Order f!\nTERMS Deposit With Order, Balance on Delivery.\nLUo PimranOQ New A11 wo1 Fabric3 Workmanship Newest 11\nIID UUdldlUCB Styles-FiWQuick Delivery. l\nANTICIPATE YOUR FALL REQUIREMENTS NOW.\nJUL BAUER\nil\nII\n3\nmi\nThrifty Buy\ni j\nII\nf x\n'X.. Fat MVVVMM.-,\"''iV'\nCO. W H.\nFOX NET\nCorner Ninth and Carter Streets\ners Mention\nWp of for a few bargains for those who wish to make their dollars do double duty. We\nlist only a few of the numerous bargains that can be had. You must come to really appre\nciate not only these bargains, biit the numerous others that await you.\nPERCALE\nThirty-one-inch Percale; fast colors; only\nTwenty-seven-inch Percale; fast colors;\nthe best materials; pe